# This short essay is filled with contradictions.

# Burke's clear "definition" of proverb in paragraph 12
# and his initial discussion in paragraph 2 suggest that
# proverbs should be classified by situation.
# But he never identifies the situation of a proverb.

# His fuzzy statement of "purpose" in paragraph 11
# suggests that proverbs should be classified by action.

# There is no consistent principle of classification.
# Burke's categories are a strange blend of
# actions (strategies) and situations.

# His clear statement of "identity" between strategy and
# attitude in paragraph 12 is contradicted in paragraph 13
# by an apparent "causality" relation between the two.

# When Burke discusses "other ways" in paragraphs 10 and 13,
# he assigns one proverb to multiple categories.
